The definition of `IsInternal` for submodules is that the set of submodules is independent and their internal sum is the whole module. But we're trying to prove the first part - that the set is independent.

The goal is `iSupIndep fun p => ↑p c`. 

The definition of `iSupIndep` is that any finite subset where all elements are non-zero has a non-zero sum.

So we need to show that for any finite subset `S` of `fun p => ↑p c`, if for all `p ∈ S`, `↑p c ≠ 0`, then `∑ p ∈ S, ↑p c ≠ 0`.

But `fun p => ↑p c` is just the set of submodules `{p.val c | p ∈ I}`. 

Since `I` is a direct sum decomposition, `I` is independent. So any finite subset of `I` that is non-zero has a non-zero sum. 

When we restrict to a point `c`, the resulting set is a subset of `I`, so it should also be independent.

